# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: polynomial-hierarchy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] In computational complexity theory, an **alternating Turing machine** (**ATM**) is a non-deterministic Turing machine (**NTM**) with a rule for accepting computations that generalizes the rules used in the definition of the complexity classes NP and co-NP.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] The concept of an ATM was set forth by Chandra and Stockmeyer and independently by Kozen in 1976, with a joint journal publication in 1981.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] The definition of NP uses the *existential mode* of computation: if *any* choice leads to an accepting state, then the whole computation accepts.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] The definition of co-NP uses the *universal mode* of computation: only if *all* choices lead to an accepting state does the whole computation accept.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] An alternating Turing machine (or to be more precise, the definition of acceptance for such a machine) alternates between these modes.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] An **alternating Turing machine** is a non-deterministic Turing machine whose states are divided into two sets: **existential states** and **universal states**.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] An existential state is accepting if some transition leads to an accepting state; a universal state is accepting if every transition leads to an accepting state.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] (Thus a universal state with no transitions accepts unconditionally; an existential state with no transitions rejects unconditionally).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] The machine as a whole accepts if the initial state is accepting.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] If *M* is in a state $q\in Q$ with $g(q)=accept$ then that configuration is said to be *accepting*, and if $g(q)=reject$ the configuration is said to be *rejecting*.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] A configuration with $g(q)=\wedge$ is said to be accepting if all configurations reachable in one step are accepting, and rejecting if some configuration reachable in one step is rejecting.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] A configuration with $g(q)=\vee$ is said to be accepting when there exists some configuration reachable in one step that is accepting and rejecting when all configurations reachable in one step are rejecting (this is the type of all states in a classical NTM except the final state).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] *M* is said to accept an input string *w* if the initial configuration of *M* (the state of *M* is $q_{0}$ , the head is at the left end of the tape, and the tape contains *w*) is accepting, and to reject if the initial configuration is rejecting.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] Note that it is impossible for a configuration to be both accepting and rejecting, however, some configurations may be neither accepting or rejecting, due to the possibility of nonterminating computations.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] When deciding if a configuration of an ATM is accepting or rejecting using the above definition, it is not always necessary to examine all configurations reachable from the current configuration.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] In particular, an existential configuration can be labelled as accepting if any successor configuration is found to be accepting, and a universal configuration can be labelled as rejecting if any successor configuration is found to be rejecting.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] An ATM decides a formal language in time $t(n)$ if, on any input of length n, examining configurations only up to $t(n)$ steps is sufficient to label the initial configuration as accepting or rejecting.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] An ATM decides a language in space $s(n)$ if examining configurations that do not modify tape cells beyond the $s(n)$ cell from the left is sufficient.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] A language that is decided by some ATM in time $c\cdot t(n)$ for some constant $c>0$ is said to be in the class ${\mathsf {ATIME}}(t(n))$ , and a language decided in space $c\cdot s(n)$ is said to be in the class ${\mathsf {ASPACE}}(s(n))$ .
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] Perhaps the most natural problem for alternating machines to solve is the quantified Boolean formula problem, which is a generalization of the Boolean satisfiability problem in which each variable can be bound by either an existential or a universal quantifier.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] The alternating machine branches existentially to try all possible values of an existentially quantified variable and universally to try all possible values of a universally quantified variable, in the left-to-right order in which they are bound.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] After deciding a value for all quantified variables, the machine accepts if the resulting Boolean formula evaluates to true, and rejects if it evaluates to false.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] Such a machine decides quantified Boolean formulas in time $n^{2}$ and space n .
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] The Boolean satisfiability problem can be viewed as the special case where all variables are existentially quantified, allowing ordinary nondeterminism, which uses only existential branching, to solve it efficiently.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] These are similar to the definitions of P, PSPACE, and EXPTIME, considering the resources used by an ATM rather than a deterministic Turing machine.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] A more general form of these relationships is expressed by the parallel computation thesis.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] An **alternating Turing machine with *k* alternations** is an alternating Turing machine that switches from an existential to a universal state or vice versa no more than *k*−1 times.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] (It is an alternating Turing machine whose states are divided into *k* sets.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] The states in even-numbered sets are universal and the states in odd-numbered sets are existential (or vice versa).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] ${\mathsf {ATIME}}(C,j)=\Sigma _{j}{\mathsf {TIME}}(C)$ is the class of languages decidable in time $f\in C$ by a machine beginning in an existential state and alternating at most $j-1$ times.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] It is called the jth level of the ${\mathsf {TIME}}(C)$ hierarchy.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] ${\mathsf {coATIME}}(C,j)=\Pi _{j}{\mathsf {TIME}}(C)$ is defined in the same way, but beginning in a universal state; it consists of the complements of the languages in ${\mathsf {ATIME}}(f,j)$ .
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] ${\mathsf {ASPACE}}(C,j)=\Sigma _{j}{\mathsf {SPACE}}(C)$ is defined similarly for space bounded computation.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] Consider the circuit minimization problem: given a circuit *A* computing a Boolean function *f* and a number *n*, determine if there is a circuit with at most *n* gates that computes the same function *f*.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] It is said that a hierarchy *collapses* to level j if every language in level $k\geq j$ of the hierarchy is in its level j.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] As a corollary of the Immerman–Szelepcsényi theorem, the logarithmic space hierarchy collapses to its first level.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] As a corollary the ${\mathsf {SPACE}}(f)$ hierarchy collapses to its first level when $f=\Omega (\log )$ is space constructible.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] An alternating Turing machine in polynomial time with *k* alternations, starting in an existential (respectively, universal) state can decide all the problems in the class $\Sigma _{k}^{p}$ (respectively, $\Pi _{k}^{p}$ ).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] These classes are sometimes denoted $\Sigma _{k}{\rm {P}}$ and $\Pi _{k}{\rm {P}}$ , respectively.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] See the polynomial hierarchy article for details.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/alternating-turing-machine] Another special case of time hierarchies is the logarithmic hierarchy.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] That is, if we assume that NP, the class of nondeterministic polynomial time problems, can be contained in the non-uniform polynomial time complexity class P/poly, then this assumption implies the collapse of the polynomial hierarchy at its second level.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] Such a collapse is believed unlikely, so the theorem is generally viewed by complexity theorists as evidence for the nonexistence of polynomial size circuits for SAT or for other NP-complete problems.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] A proof that such circuits do not exist would imply that P ≠ NP.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] As P/poly contains all problems solvable in randomized polynomial time (Adleman's theorem), the theorem is also evidence that the use of randomization does not lead to polynomial time algorithms for NP-complete problems.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] The Karp–Lipton theorem is named after Richard M.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] Variants of the theorem state that, under the same assumption, **MA** = **AM**, and **PH** collapses to **SP 2** complexity class.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] There are stronger conclusions possible if PSPACE, or some other complexity classes are assumed to have polynomial-sized circuits; see P/poly.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] If NP is assumed to be a subset of BPP (which is a subset of P/poly), then the polynomial hierarchy collapses to BPP.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] If coNP is assumed to be subset of NP/poly, then the polynomial hierarchy collapses to its third level.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] Suppose that polynomial sized circuits for SAT not only exist, but also that they could be constructed by a polynomial time algorithm.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] Then this supposition implies that SAT itself could be solved by a polynomial time algorithm that constructs the circuit and then applies it.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] That is, efficiently constructible circuits for SAT would lead to a stronger collapse, P = NP.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] The assumption of the Karp–Lipton theorem, that these circuits exist, is weaker.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] But it is still possible for an algorithm in the complexity class $\Sigma _{2}$ to *guess* a correct circuit for SAT.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] where $\psi$ is any polynomial-time computable predicate.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] The existential power of the first quantifier in this predicate can be used to guess a correct circuit for SAT, and the universal power of the second quantifier can be used to verify that the circuit is correct.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] Once this circuit is guessed and verified, the algorithm in class $\Sigma _{2}$ can use it as a subroutine for solving other problems.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] To understand the Karp–Lipton proof in more detail, we consider the problem of testing whether a circuit *c* is a correct circuit for solving SAT instances of a given size, and show that this circuit testing problem belongs to $\Pi _{1}$ .
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] That is, there exists a polynomial time computable predicate *V* such that *c* is a correct circuit if and only if, for all polynomially-bounded *z*, *V*(*c*,*z*) is true.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] The first of these two properties is already in the form of problems in class $\Pi _{1}$ .
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] To verify the second property, we use the *self-reducibility* property of SAT.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] Self-reducibility describes the phenomenon that, if we can quickly test whether a SAT instance is solvable, we can almost as quickly find an explicit solution to the instance.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] To find a solution to an instance *s*, choose one of the Boolean variables *x* that is input to *s*, and make two smaller instances *s*0 and *s*1 where *s**i* denotes the formula formed by replacing *x* with the constant *i*.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] Once these two smaller instances have been constructed, apply the test for solvability to each of them.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] If one of these two tests returns that the smaller instance is satisfiable, continue solving that instance until a complete solution has been derived.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] Thus, we can test in $\Pi _{1}$ whether *c* is a valid circuit for solving SAT.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] See Random self-reducibility for more information.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] The Karp–Lipton theorem can be restated as a result about Boolean formulas with polynomially-bounded quantifiers.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] where $\psi$ is a polynomial-time computable predicate.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] The Karp–Lipton theorem states that this type of formula can be transformed in polynomial time into an equivalent formula in which the quantifiers appear in the opposite order; such a formula belongs to $\Sigma _{2}$ .
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] That is, if *c* is a valid circuit for SAT, then this subformula is equivalent to the unquantified formula *c*(*s*(*x*)).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] where *V* is the formula used to verify that *c* really is a valid circuit using self-reducibility, as described above.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] This equivalent formula has its quantifiers in the opposite order, as desired.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] Therefore, there exists a family of circuits $C_{n}$ that solves satisfiability on input of length *n*.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] Using self-reducibility, there exists a family of circuits $D_{n}$ which outputs a satisfying assignment on true instances.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] In this case, no circuit *D* can output an assignment making $\phi (x,D(x,z),z)\;$ true.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] The proof has shown that a $\Pi _{2}$ set L is in $\Sigma _{2}$ .
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] What's more, if the $\Pi _{2}$ formula is true, then the circuit *D* will work against any *x*.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] If the $\Pi _{2}$ formula is false, then *x* making the formula (1) false will work against any circuit.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] This property means a stronger collapse, namely to **SP 2** complexity class (i.e. $\Pi _{2}\subseteq {\mathsf {S}}_{2}^{P}\subseteq \Sigma _{2}$ ).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] which proves L is in the smaller class **MA**.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] There exists a language $L\in \Sigma _{4}-{\mathsf {SIZE}}(n^{k})$ (the proof uses diagonalization technique).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] A stronger version of Karp–Lipton theorem strengthens Kannan's theorem to: for any *k*, there exists a language $L\in {\mathsf {S}}_{2}^{P}-{\mathsf {SIZE}}(n^{k})$ .
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/karp-lipton-theorem] It is also known that **PP** is not contained in ${\mathsf {SIZE}}(n^{k})$ , which was proved by Vinodchandran.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] In complexity theory and computability theory, an **oracle machine** is an abstract machine that can query a black box called an **oracle**, which is able to give an answer to any instance of a certain problem ⁠ R ⁠ in a single operation.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] The problem ⁠ R ⁠ can be of any complexity class, or it can even be an undecidable problem such as the halting problem.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] If another problem ⁠ $R'$ ⁠ is reducible to ⁠ R ⁠ in polynomial time, then the oracle machine (with the ⁠ R ⁠-oracle) can solve ⁠ $R'$ ⁠ in polynomial time; one can say that ⁠ $R'$ ⁠ is in the **relativized complexity class** ⁠ ${\mathsf {P}}^{R}$ ⁠.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] Other relativized complexity classes such as ⁠ ${\mathsf {NP}}^{R}$ ⁠ can be defined analogously.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] An oracle machine can be conceived as a Turing machine connected to an **oracle**.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] The oracle, in this context, is an entity capable of solving some problem, which for example may be a decision problem or a function problem.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] The problem does not have to be computable; the oracle is not assumed to be a Turing machine or computer program.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] An oracle machine can perform all of the usual operations of a Turing machine, and can also query the oracle to obtain a solution to any instance of the computational problem for that oracle.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] For example, if the problem is a decision problem for a set *A* of natural numbers, the oracle machine supplies the oracle with a natural number, and the oracle responds with "yes" or "no" stating whether that number is an element of *A*.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] There are many equivalent definitions of oracle Turing machines, as discussed below.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] The one presented here is from van Melkebeek (2003, p.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] From time to time, the oracle machine may enter the ASK state.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] The effect of changing to the ASK state is thus to receive, in a single step, a solution to the problem instance that is written on the oracle tape.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] There are many alternative definitions to the one presented above.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] Many of these are specialized for the case where the oracle solves a decision problem.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] These definitions are equivalent from the point of view of Turing computability: a function is oracle-computable from a given oracle under all of these definitions if it is oracle-computable under any of them.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] The definitions are not equivalent, however, from the point of view of computational complexity.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] A definition such as the one by van Melkebeek, using an oracle tape that may have its own alphabet, is required in general.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] The complexity class of decision problems solvable by an algorithm in class *A* with an oracle for a language *L* is called *A**L*.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] For example, PSAT is the class of problems solvable in polynomial time by a deterministic Turing machine with an oracle for the Boolean satisfiability problem.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] When a language *L* is complete for some class *B*, then *A**L*=*A**B* provided that machines in *A* can execute reductions used in the completeness definition of class *B*.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] In particular, since SAT is NP-complete with respect to polynomial time reductions, PSAT=PNP.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] However, if *A* = DLOGTIME, then *A*SAT may not equal *A*NP.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] (The definition of $A^{B}$ given above is not completely standard.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] In some contexts, such as the proof of the time and space hierarchy theorems, it is more useful to assume that the abstract machine defining class A only has access to a single oracle for one language.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] It is understood that NP ⊆ PNP, but the question of whether NPNP, PNP, NP, and P are equal remains tentative at best.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] It is believed they are different, and this leads to the definition of the polynomial hierarchy.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] Oracle machines are useful for investigating the relationship between complexity classes P and NP, by considering the relationship between P*A* and NP*A* for an oracle *A*.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] In particular, it has been shown there exist languages *A* and *B* such that P*A*=NP*A* and P*B*≠NP*B*.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] The fact the P = NP question relativizes both ways is taken as evidence that answering this question is difficult, because any proof technique that *relativizes* (i.e., is unaffected by the addition of an oracle) will not answer the P = NP question.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] One may consider the case where an oracle is chosen randomly from among all possible oracles (an infinite set).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] It has been shown in this case, that with probability 1, P*A*≠NP*A*.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] When a question is true for almost all oracles, it is said to be true *for a random oracle*.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] This choice of terminology is justified by the fact that random oracles support a statement with probability 0 or 1 only.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] (This follows from Kolmogorov's zero–one law.) This is only weak evidence that P≠NP, since a statement may be true for a random oracle but false for ordinary Turing machines; for example, IP*A*≠PSPACE*A* for a random oracle *A* but IP = PSPACE.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] A machine with an oracle for the halting problem can determine whether particular Turing machines will halt on particular inputs, but it cannot determine, in general, whether oracle machines like itself (i.e. equipped with an oracle for the halting problem) will halt.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] This creates a hierarchy of machines, each with a more powerful halting oracle and an even harder halting problem.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] This hierarchy of machines can be used to define the *arithmetical hierarchy*.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] In cryptography, oracles are used to make arguments for the security of cryptographic protocols where a hash function is used.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] A security reduction (proof of security) for the protocol is given in the case where, instead of a hash function, a random oracle answers each query randomly but consistently; the oracle is assumed to be available to all parties including the attacker, as the hash function is.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/oracle-machine] Such a proof shows that unless the attacker solves the hard problem at the heart of the security reduction, they must make use of some interesting property of the hash function to break the protocol; they cannot treat the hash function as a black box (i.e., as a random oracle).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] In computational complexity theory, the **polynomial hierarchy** (sometimes called the **polynomial-time hierarchy**) is a hierarchy of complexity classes that generalize the classes **NP** and **co-NP**.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] Each class in the hierarchy is contained within **PSPACE**.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] The hierarchy can be defined using oracle machines or alternating Turing machines.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] It is a resource-bounded counterpart to the arithmetical hierarchy and analytical hierarchy from mathematical logic.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] The union of the classes in the hierarchy is denoted **PH**.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] Classes within the hierarchy have complete problems (with respect to polynomial-time reductions) that ask if quantified Boolean formulae hold, for formulae with restrictions on the quantifier order.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] It is known that equality between classes on the same level or consecutive levels in the hierarchy would imply a "collapse" of the hierarchy to that level.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] There are multiple equivalent definitions of the classes of the polynomial hierarchy.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] where P is the set of decision problems solvable in polynomial time.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] where $\mathrm {P} ^{\rm {A}}$ is the set of decision problems solvable in polynomial time by a Turing machine augmented by an oracle for some complete problem in class A; the classes $\mathrm {NP} ^{\rm {A}}$ and $\mathrm {coNP} ^{\rm {A}}$ are defined analogously.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] For example, $\Sigma _{1}^{\mathrm {P} }=\mathrm {NP} ,\Pi _{1}^{\mathrm {P} }=\mathrm {coNP}$ , and $\Delta _{2}^{\mathrm {P} }=\mathrm {P^{NP}}$ is the class of problems solvable in polynomial time by a deterministic Turing machine with an oracle for some NP-complete problem.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] where $\langle x,w\rangle \in \{0,1\}^{*}$ is some standard encoding of the pair of binary strings *x* and *w* as a single binary string.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] The language *L* represents a set of ordered pairs of strings, where the first string *x* is a member of $\exists ^{p}L$ , and the second string *w* is a "short" ( $|w|\leq p(|x|)$ ) witness testifying that *x* is a member of $\exists ^{p}L$ .
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] In other words, $x\in \exists ^{p}L$ if and only if there exists a short witness *w* such that $\langle x,w\rangle \in L$ .
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] The classes **NP** and **co-NP** can be defined as $\mathrm {NP} =\exists ^{\mathrm {P} }\mathrm {P}$ , and $\mathrm {coNP} =\forall ^{\mathrm {P} }\mathrm {P}$ , where **P** is the class of all feasibly (polynomial-time) decidable languages.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] This definition reflects the close connection between the polynomial hierarchy and the arithmetical hierarchy, where **R** and **RE** play roles analogous to **P** and **NP**, respectively.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] The analytic hierarchy is also defined in a similar way to give a hierarchy of subsets of the real numbers.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] An alternating Turing machine is a non-deterministic Turing machine with non-final states partitioned into existential and universal states.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] It is eventually accepting from its current configuration if: it is in an existential state and can transition into some eventually accepting configuration; or, it is in a universal state and every transition is into some eventually accepting configuration; or, it is in an accepting state.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] We define $\Sigma _{k}^{\mathrm {P} }$ to be the class of languages accepted by an alternating Turing machine in polynomial time such that the initial state is an existential state and every path the machine can take swaps at most *k* – 1 times between existential and universal states.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] We define $\Pi _{k}^{\mathrm {P} }$ similarly, except that the initial state is a universal state.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] If we omit the requirement of at most *k* – 1 swaps between the existential and universal states, so that we only require that our alternating Turing machine runs in polynomial time, then we have the definition of the class **AP**, which is equal to **PSPACE**.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] The union of all classes in the polynomial hierarchy is the complexity class **PH**.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] Unlike the arithmetic and analytic hierarchies, whose inclusions are known to be proper, it is an open question whether any of these inclusions are proper, though it is widely believed that they all are.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] The case in which **NP** = **PH** is also termed as a *collapse* of the **PH** to *the second level*.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] The case **P** = **NP** corresponds to a collapse of **PH** to **P**.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] The question of collapse to the first level is generally thought to be extremely difficult.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] Most researchers do not believe in a collapse, even to the second level.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] The polynomial hierarchy is an analogue (at much lower complexity) of the exponential hierarchy and arithmetical hierarchy.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] It is known that PH is contained within PSPACE, but it is not known whether the two classes are equal.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] One useful reformulation of this problem is that PH = PSPACE if and only if second-order logic over finite structures gains no additional power from the addition of a transitive closure operator over relations of relations (i.e., over the second-order variables).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] If the polynomial hierarchy has any complete problems, then it has only finitely many distinct levels.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] Since there are PSPACE-complete problems, we know that if PSPACE = PH, then the polynomial hierarchy must collapse, since a PSPACE-complete problem would be a $\Sigma _{k}^{\mathrm {P} }$ -complete problem for some *k*.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] Each class in the polynomial hierarchy contains $\leq _{\rm {m}}^{\mathrm {P} }$ -complete problems (problems complete under polynomial-time many-one reductions).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] Furthermore, each class in the polynomial hierarchy is *closed under $\leq _{\rm {m}}^{\mathrm {P} }$ -reductions*: meaning that for a class C in the hierarchy and a language $L\in {\mathcal {C}}$ , if $A\leq _{\rm {m}}^{\mathrm {P} }L$ , then $A\in {\mathcal {C}}$ as well.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] In other words, if a language is defined based on some oracle in C, then we can assume that it is defined based on a complete problem for C.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] Complete problems therefore act as "representatives" of the class for which they are complete.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/ph-complexity] There is some evidence that BQP, the class of problems solvable in polynomial time by a quantum computer, is not contained in PH; however, it is also believed that PH is not contained in BQP.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] In computational complexity theory, the language **TQBF** is a formal language consisting of the **true quantified Boolean formulas**.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] A (fully) quantified Boolean formula is a formula in quantified propositional logic (also known as Second-order propositional logic) where every variable is quantified (or bound), using either existential or universal quantifiers, at the beginning of the sentence.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Such a formula is equivalent to either true or false (since there are no free variables).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] If such a formula evaluates to true, then that formula is in the language TQBF.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] It is also known as **QSAT** (Quantified SAT).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] In computational complexity theory, the **quantified Boolean formula problem** (**QBF**) is a generalization of the Boolean satisfiability problem in which both existential quantifiers and universal quantifiers can be applied to each variable.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Put another way, it asks whether a quantified sentential form over a set of Boolean variables is true or false.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] QBF is the canonical complete problem for PSPACE, the class of problems solvable by a deterministic or nondeterministic Turing machine in polynomial space and unlimited time.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Given the formula in the form of an abstract syntax tree, the problem can be solved easily by a set of mutually recursive procedures which evaluate the formula.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Such an algorithm uses space proportional to the height of the tree, which is linear in the worst case, but uses time exponential in the number of quantifiers.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Provided that MA ⊊ PSPACE, which is widely believed, QBF cannot be solved, nor can a given solution even be verified, in either deterministic or probabilistic polynomial time (in fact, unlike the satisfiability problem, there's no known way to specify a solution succinctly).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] It can be solved using an alternating Turing machine in linear time, since AP = PSPACE, where AP is the class of problems alternating machines can solve in polynomial time.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] When the seminal result IP = PSPACE was shown (see interactive proof system), it was done by exhibiting an interactive proof system that could solve QBF by solving a particular arithmetization of the problem.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] QBF formulas have a number of useful canonical forms.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] For example, it can be shown that there is a polynomial-time many-one reduction that will move all quantifiers to the front of the formula and make them alternate between universal and existential quantifiers.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] There is another reduction that proved useful in the IP = PSPACE proof where no more than one universal quantifier is placed between each variable's use and the quantifier binding that variable.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This was critical in limiting the number of products in certain subexpressions of the arithmetization.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] A fully quantified Boolean formula can be assumed to have a very specific form, called prenex normal form.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] It has two basic parts: a portion containing only quantifiers and a portion containing an unquantified Boolean formula usually denoted as $\displaystyle \phi$ .
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] where every variable falls within the scope of some quantifier.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] By introducing dummy variables, any formula in prenex normal form can be converted into a sentence where existential and universal quantifiers alternate.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The second sentence has the same truth value but follows the restricted syntax.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Assuming fully quantified Boolean formulas to be in prenex normal form is a frequent feature of proofs.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] There is a simple recursive algorithm for determining whether a QBF is in TQBF (i.e. is true).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] If the formula contains no quantifiers, we can just return the formula.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] For every quantifier in the initial QBF, the algorithm makes two recursive calls on only a linearly smaller subproblem.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This gives the algorithm an exponential runtime O(2*n*).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Within each invocation of the algorithm, it needs to store the intermediate results of computing A and B.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Every recursive call takes off one quantifier, so the total recursive depth is linear in the number of quantifiers.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Formulas that lack quantifiers can be evaluated in space logarithmic in the number of variables.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The initial QBF was fully quantified, so there are at least as many quantifiers as variables.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This makes the TQBF language part of the PSPACE complexity class.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Despite the PSPACE-completeness of QBF, many solvers have been developed to solve these instances (This is analogous to the situation with SAT, the single existential quantifier version; even though it is NP-complete, it is still possible to solve many SAT instances heuristically).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The case where there are only 2 quantifiers, known as 2QBF, has received special attention.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The QBF solver competition QBFEVAL has been running more-or-less annually since 2004; solvers are required to read instances in QDIMACS format and either the QCIR or QAIGER formats.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] High-performing QBF solvers generally use QDPLL (a generalization of DPLL) or CEGAR.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] QBF solvers can be applied to planning (in artificial intelligence), including safe planning; the latter is critical in applications of robotics.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] QBF solvers can also be applied to bounded model checking as they provide a shorter encoding than would be needed for a SAT-based solver.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The evaluation of a QBF can be seen as a two-player game between a player who controls existentially quantified variables and a player who controls universally quantified variables.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This makes QBFs suitable for encoding reactive synthesis problems.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Similarly, QBF solvers can be used to model adversarial games in game theory.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] For example, QBF solvers can be used to find winning strategies for games of geography, which can then be automatically played interactively.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] QBF solvers can be used for formal equivalence checking, and can also be used to synthesize Boolean functions.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The Stochastic Satisfiability problem (known as SSAT) is an extension of TQBF that adds a randomizing R quantifier, views universal quantification as minimization, and existential quantification as maximization, and asks, whether the probability represented by the formula exceeds a given threshold.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] QBF can be also extended to have Henkin quantifiers.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The TQBF language serves in complexity theory as the canonical PSPACE-complete problem.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Being PSPACE-complete means that a language is in PSPACE and that the language is also PSPACE-hard.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The algorithm above shows that TQBF is in PSPACE.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Showing that TQBF is PSPACE-hard requires showing that any language in the complexity class PSPACE can be reduced to TQBF in polynomial time.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This means that, for a PSPACE language L, whether an input x is in L can be decided by checking whether $f(x)$ is in TQBF, for some function f that is required to run in polynomial time (relative to the length of the input).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Proving that TQBF is PSPACE-hard, requires specification of f.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] So, suppose that L is a PSPACE language.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This means that L can be decided by a polynomial space deterministic Turing machine (DTM).
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] We know that *T* = *O*(exp(*n*k)) for some *k*, where *n* is the length of the input, because this bounds the total number of possible configurations of the relevant DTM.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Of course, it cannot take the DTM more steps than there are possible configurations to reach $c_{\mathrm {accept} }$ unless it enters a loop, in which case it will never reach $c_{\mathrm {accept} }$ anyway.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] At this stage of the proof, we have already reduced the question of whether an input formula w (encoded, of course, in $c_{\text{start}}$ ) is in L to the question of whether the QBF $\phi _{c_{\text{start}},c_{\text{accept}},T}$ , i.e., $f(w)$ , is in TQBF.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The remainder of this proof proves that f can be computed in polynomial time.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] For $t=1$ , computation of $\phi _{c_{1},c_{2},t}$ is straightforward—either one of the configurations changes to the other in one step or it does not.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Since the Turing Machine that our formula represents is deterministic, this presents no problem.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] For $t>1$ , computation of $\phi _{c_{1},c_{2},t}$ involves a recursive evaluation, looking for a so-called "middle point" $m_{1}$ .
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This converts the question of whether $c_{1}$ can reach $c_{2}$ in t steps to the question of whether $c_{1}$ reaches a middle point $m_{1}$ in $t/2$ steps, which itself reaches $c_{2}$ in $t/2$ steps.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The answer to the latter question of course gives the answer to the former.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Now, t is only bounded by T, which is exponential (and so not polynomial) in the length of the input.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Additionally, each recursive layer virtually doubles the length of the formula.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] (The variable $m_{1}$ is only one midpoint—for greater t, there are more stops along the way, so to speak.) So the time required to recursively evaluate $\phi _{c_{1},c_{2},t}$ in this manner could be exponential as well, simply because the formula could become exponentially large.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This problem is solved by universally quantifying using variables $c_{3}$ and $c_{4}$ over the configuration pairs (e.g., $\{(c_{1},m_{1}),(m_{1},c_{2})\}$ ), which prevents the length of the formula from expanding due to recursive layers.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This version of the formula can indeed be computed in polynomial time, since any one instance of it can be computed in polynomial time.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Thus, $\forall L\in {\mathsf {PSPACE}},L\leq _{p}\mathrm {TQBF}$ , so TQBF is PSPACE-hard.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Together with the above result that TQBF is in PSPACE, this completes the proof that TQBF is a PSPACE-complete language.
[src:polynomial-hierarchy/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This construction can be run in logspace, meaning that TQBF is PSPACE-complete in he sense of logspace many-one reduction.
